File: e2e/dispatch-resilience.e2e.ts, lines 522-609.

The 'server-side dispatch timeout when extension WS is replaced' test creates a `timeoutClient` at line 522 and initializes it at line 523. If an exception is thrown inside the try block (lines 572-588) — for example if `toolCallPromise` at line 576 rejects with a transport error — the `finally` at line 587 only closes `fakeWs`. The `timeoutClient.close()` at line 594 is outside this try/finally, so it is skipped on exception.

Fix: restructure the cleanup so that `timeoutClient.close()` and `testServer.setSlow(0)` are in a `finally` block that encompasses all code after their creation. One approach:

```typescript
const timeoutClient = createMcpClient(mcpServer.port, mcpServer.secret);
await timeoutClient.initialize();
try {
  // ... existing code (fetchWsInfo, setSlow, toolCallPromise, fakeWs, etc.) ...
  // Move the existing inner try/finally for fakeWs inside here
} finally {
  await testServer.setSlow(0);
  await timeoutClient.close();
}
```

Do NOT change the test assertions or timing expectations. The existing inner try/finally for fakeWs cleanup (lines 572-589) should remain — nest it inside the outer try/finally.
